Indexes and Constraints
🧠 1. INDEX (Speed Booster ⚡)
👉 Index = shortcut to find data faster
Think:
> Without index → scan whole table (slow)
With index → jump directly to data (fast)
📚 Like a book index page
---
🔹 Example
Table: students
id	name	age
1	Rahul	22
2	Amit	19
...	...	...

🔹 Without Index
SELECT * FROM students WHERE name = 'Rahul';
👉 Database checks every row 😴

🔹 Create Index
CREATE INDEX idx_name ON students(name);

🔹 With Index
👉 Now DB directly finds “Rahul” ⚡

🧠 When to Use Index?
✅ Frequently searched columns
name
email
id
foreign keys

⚠️ When NOT to Use
❌ Small tables
❌ Columns with many duplicate values
❌ Too many indexes (slows INSERT/UPDATE)

🔹 Types of Index (Basic)
Single Column Index
Composite Index
CREATE INDEX idx_name_age ON students(name, age);

⚠️ Important Note
👉 Index improves:
SELECT 🔥
👉 But slows:
INSERT
UPDATE
DELETE
---
🧠 2. CONSTRAINTS (Data Rules 🔒)
👉 Constraints = Rules applied on table
👉 They ensure:
Data is correct
No garbage data

🔹 Types of Constraints
1️⃣ PRIMARY KEY
👉 Unique + NOT NULL
CREATE TABLE students (
  id INT PRIMARY KEY,
  name VARCHAR(50)
);
👉 No duplicate IDs

2️⃣ FOREIGN KEY
👉 Connects two tables
CREATE TABLE orders (
  id INT,
  student_id INT,
  FOREIGN KEY (student_id) REFERENCES students(id)
);
👉 Ensures valid relationship

3️⃣ UNIQUE
👉 No duplicate values
email VARCHAR(100) UNIQUE

4️⃣ NOT NULL
👉 Cannot be empty
name VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL

5️⃣ CHECK
👉 Apply condition
age INT CHECK (age >= 18)

6️⃣ DEFAULT
👉 Set default value
status VARCHAR(20) DEFAULT 'active'

🧠 Real-Life Example
👉 User signup system:
CREATE TABLE users (
  id INT PRIMARY KEY,
  email VARCHAR(100) UNIQUE,
  age INT CHECK (age >= 18),
  status VARCHAR(20) DEFAULT 'active'
);

🔥 Index vs Constraint (Important)
Feature	Index	Constraint
Purpose	Speed	Data safety
Affects	Performance	Data validity
Example	Search fast	No duplicate

⚠️ Common Mistakes
❌ Too many indexes
👉 Slows database

❌ No constraints
👉 Garbage data enters system
